{{Bahá'í sidebar}}
The '''Bahá'í Faith in Colombia''' begins with references to the country in Bahá'í literature as early as 1916,<ref name="Tabs">{{cite book |author = `Abdu'l-Bahá |authorlink = `Abdu'l-Bahá |origyear = 1916-17 |year = 1991 |title = Tablets of the Divine Plan |edition = Paperback |publisher = Bahá'í Publishing Trust |location = Wilmette, Illinois, USA |isbn = 0-87743-233-3 |url =http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/ab/TDP/tdp-6.html | pages = 31–32}}</ref> with [[Bahá'í Faith|Bahá'ís]] visiting as early as 1927.<ref name="memorium">{{Citation  | title = In Memoriam| journal = The Bahá'í World | volume = XVIII  | publisher = Bahá'í World Centre  | pages = 733–736  | year = 1986  | url = http://bahai-library.com/books/bw18/720-748.html  | isbn = 0-85398-234-1  | author = prepared under the supervision of the Universal House of Justice.}}</ref> The first Colombian joined the religion in 1929<ref name="BN577">{{cite magazine | title = Around the World; Colombia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1979 | number = 577 | page =19 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=960}}</ref> and the first Bahá'í [[Local Spiritual Assembly]] was elected in [[Bogotá]] in 1944<ref name="BN172">{{cite magazine | title =South America |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1944 | number = 169 | page =7 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=624}}</ref> with the beginning of the arrival of coordinated [[Pioneering (Bahá'í)|pioneers]] from the [[United States]] and achieved an independent [[National Spiritual Assembly]] in 1961.<ref name="alamb">{{cite book | last = Lamb  | first = Artemus  | title = The Beginnings of the Bahá'í Faith in Latin America:Some Remembrances, English Revised and Amplified Edition | publisher = M L VanOrman Enterprises  |date=November 1995  | location = 1405 Killarney Drive, West Linn OR, 97068, United States of America | url =http://bahai-library.com/lamb_bahai_latin_america}}</ref> By 1963 there were eleven local assemblies.<ref name="stats">{{cite book | title = The Bahá'í Faith: 1844-1963: Information Statistical and Comparative, Including the Achievements of the Ten Year International Bahá'í Teaching & Consolidation Plan 1953-1963 | publisher = [[Hand of the Cause|Hands of the Cause]] Residing in the Holy Land | year = 1963  | location = Haifa, Israel | pages = 16, 19, 77 | url = http://bahai-library.com/handscause_statistics_1953-63&chapter=1#22 | isbn = }}</ref> In the 1980s institutions were developed in Colombia that have influenced activities inside and independent of the religion in other countries: [[FUNDAEC]]<ref name="Rural">{{Cite conference | first = | last = CRECE: Centro de Estudios Regionales, Cafeteros y Empresariales | authorlink = CRECE | title = Successful Alternatives for Rural Education: Tutorial Learning System (TLS) and New School Methodology Rural Post-Primary | booktitle = Regional Policy Dialogue on Education and Human Resources Training Network, Second Meeting: Secondary Education | publisher = Inter-American Development Bank | date = August 2001 | location = Manizales, Colombia | url = http://idbdocs.iadb.org/wsdocs/getdocument.aspx?docnum=776328 | accessdate = 2008-05-05}}</ref><ref name="BN634">{{cite magazine| title =  Canada - Association's 8th annual Conference | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=January 1984 | number = 634 |pages=8–10| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=50}}</ref> and the [[Ruhi Institute]].<ref name="BN648">{{cite magazine| title = The World; Honduras | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1985 | number = 648 | page =15| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=354}}</ref>  The [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] (relying mostly on the [[World Christian Encyclopedia]]) estimated some 70,000 Bahá'ís (0.2% of the population) in 2005,<ref name="WCE-05">{{cite web| title = Most Baha'i Nations (2005) | work = QuickLists > Compare Nations > Religions > | publisher = The Association of Religion Data Archives | year = 2005| url =http://www.thearda.com/QuickLists/QuickList_40c.asp | accessdate = 2009-07-04}}</ref> and about the same in 2010.<ref name=ARDA2010>{{cite web | title = Most Baha'i Nations (2010) | work = QuickLists > Compare Nations > Religions > | publisher = The Association of Religion Data Archives | year = 2010 | url =http://www.thearda.com/QL2010/QuickList_40.asp | accessdate = Feb 12, 2015  }}</ref>

==`Abdu'l-Bahá's Tablets of the Divine Plan==
[[`Abdu'l-Bahá]], the son of the founder of the religion, wrote a series of letters, or [[tablets (religious)|tablets]], to the followers of the religion in the [[United States]] in 1916-1917; these letters were compiled together in the book titled [[Tablets of the Divine Plan]].  The sixth of the tablets was the first to mention [[Latin America]]n regions and was written on April 8, 1916, but was delayed in being presented in the United States until 1919 &mdash; after the end of [[World War I]] and the [[Spanish flu]]. The sixth tablet was translated and presented by [[Mirza Ahmad Sohrab]] on April 4, 1919, and published in [[Star of the West (Bahá'í magazine)|Star of the West]] magazine on December 12, 1919.<ref>{{cite book| last = Abbas | first = 'Abdu'l-Bahá |others=Mirza Ahmad Sohrab (trans. and comments) | title = Tablets, Instructions and Words of Explanation |date=April 1919 | url =http://bahai-library.com/abdulbaha_tablets_instructions_explanation}}</ref>

<blockquote>"His Holiness [[Christ]] says: Travel ye to the East and to the West of the world and summon the people to the [[Kingdom of God]]. ... the republic of Mexico...to be familiar with the [[Spanish language]]...[[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]], [[El Salvador|Salvador]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Panama]] and the seventh country [[Belize]]...Attach great importance to the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] population of America...Likewise the islands of ...[[Cuba]], [[Haiti]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Jamaica]], ... [[Bahama]] Islands, even the small [[Watling Island]]...[[Haiti]] and [[Santo Domingo]]...the islands of [[Bermuda]]... the republics of the continent of South America—[[Colombia]], [[Ecuador]], [[Peru]], [[Brazil]], [[The Guianas]], [[Bolivia]], [[Chile]], [[Argentina]], [[Uruguay]], [[Paraguay]], [[Venezuela]]; also the islands to the north, east and west of South America, such as [[Falkland Islands]], the [[Galápagos Islands|Galapagòs]], [[Juan Fernández Islands|Juan Fernandez]], [[Trinidad and Tobago|Tobago and Trinidad]]...."<ref name="Tabs"/></blockquote>

Following the release of these tablets and then `Abdu'l-Bahá's death in 1921, a few Bahá'ís began moving to or at least visiting Latin America. In 1927 [[Leonora Armstrong]] was the first Bahá'í to visit and give lectures about the religion in Colombia as part of her plan to compliment and complete [[Martha Root]]'s unfulfilled intention of visiting all the Latin American countries for the purpose of presenting the religion to an audience.<ref name="memorium"/> Aura Sanchez of Bogotá is credited as the first Colombian Bahá'í. She joined the religion in 1929 after hearing of the religion from an American who was in that country.<ref name="BN577"/>

==Early phase==
[[Shoghi Effendi]], who was named `Abdu'l-Bahá's successor, wrote a [[Telegraphy|cable]] on May 1, 1936 to the [[Bahá'í administration#National|Bahá'í Annual Convention]] of the United States and Canada, and asked for the systematic implementation of `Abdu'l-Bahá's vision to begin.<ref name="alamb"/>  In his cable he wrote:
<blockquote>
"Appeal to assembled delegates ponder historic appeal voiced by 'Abdu'l-Bahá in ''Tablets of the Divine Plan''. Urge earnest deliberation with incoming National Assembly to insure its complete fulfillment. First century of Bahá'í Era drawing to a close. Humanity entering outer fringes most perilous stage its existence. Opportunities of present hour unimaginably precious. Would to God every State within American Republic and every Republic in American continent might ere termination of this glorious century embrace the light of the Faith of Bahá'u'lláh and establish structural basis of His World Order."<ref>{{cite book |first = Shoghi |last = Effendi |authorlink = Shoghi Effendi |origyear =  |year = 1947 |title = Messages to America  |publisher = Bahá'í Publishing Committee |location = Wilmette, Illinois, USA |oclc =  5806374 |url = http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/se/MA/ma-16.html.iso8859-1?query=Appeal | page = 6}}</ref></blockquote>

Following the May 1st cable, another cable from Shoghi Effendi came on May 19 calling for permanent [[Pioneering (Bahá'í)|pioneers]] to be established in all the countries of Latin America. The Bahá'í [[National Spiritual Assembly]] of the United States and Canada was appointed the Inter-America Committee to take charge of the preparations. During the 1937 Bahá'í North American Convention, Shoghi Effendi cabled advising the convention to prolong their deliberations to permit the delegates and the National Assembly to consult on a plan that would enable Bahá'ís to go to Latin America as well as to include the completion of the outer structure of the [[Bahá'í House of Worship]] in Wilmette, Illinois.<ref name="alamb"/>  In 1937 the ''First Seven Year Plan''  (1937–44), which was an international plan designed by Shoghi Effendi, gave the American Bahá'ís the goal of establishing the Bahá'í Faith in every country in Latin America. With the spread of American Bahá'ís in Latin American, Bahá'í communities and [[Local Spiritual Assemblies]] began to form in 1938 across Latin America.<ref name="alamb"/>

The permanent Colombian Bahá'í community dates from the arrival of Gerard Sluter in 1940.<ref name="alamb"/><ref>{{cite magazine | title = Inter-America Addresses|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1940 | number = 139 | page =5 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=316}}</ref> The next pioneer to arrive was Ruth Shoock who arrived in November–December 1942.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Inter-America News|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1942 | number = 158 | page =2 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=527}}</ref> followed closely by Winifred Louise Baker in later January 1943.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Inter-America News|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1942 | number = 158 | page =2 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=527}}</ref> Carlos Nieto is credited with being the first convert - he was from Barranquilla.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = South America|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1944 | number = 169 | page =7 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=624}}</ref>

[[Dorothy Beecher Baker]], later a [[Hand of the Cause]], had a daughter, Winifred Louise Baker, who pioneered to Colombia in January 1943.<ref>{{cite magazine | title =  Dorothy Baker - Golden years of a life of service to Cause|author=Margaret H. Hildreth|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1983 | number = 623 |pages=6–11 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=814}}</ref> Later in 1943 Dorothy spent a month in Colombia visiting the Bahá'ís and her daughter.<ref>{{cite magazine |title = Excerpts from an Inter-America Report Received Prior to the Convention; South America |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1944 | number = 169 | page =7 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=624}}</ref> By January 1944 there were six Colombian converts to the religion<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Inter-America News; Colombia |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=January 1944 | number = 167 | page =8 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=624}}</ref> and they helped elect the first Bahá'í [[Local Spiritual Assembly]] which was in [[Bogotá]] that January.<ref name="BN172"/> In 1943 during the annual Bahá'í convention of the United States, Shoghi Effendi announced a Northern-and Southern- international convention which would include representatives from each state and province from the United States and Canada and each republic of Latin America. This 1944 centenary of the religion's All-America Convention's Colombian delegate was Josephina Rodriquez.<ref name=BN170>{{cite magazine | title = The Latin-American Session|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1944 | number = 170 | page =4 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=630}}</ref> By September there were 25 Bahá'ís in Bogotá with about an equal number studying the religion actively.<ref name=BN170/> By June 1945 a campaign of letter exchanges had raised an assembly in [[Mogotes]] and there were converts among people at a [[leper colony]] at [[Contratacion]]<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Briefs from Letters of Pioneer; Colombia |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1945 | number = 175 | page =10 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=730}}</ref> and individuals in Cartagena and Medellín and interested responses from several other cities.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Correspondence Teaching in Latin America |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1947 | number = 193 | page =2 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=950}}</ref> Around October 1946 Gayle Woolson took an extended trip through several towns of Colombia including Cali, Medellín, Cartagena and Barranquilla as well as some towns in Ecuador.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Latin-American News |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1946 | number = 188 | page =7 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=883}}</ref>

==Growth==
As 1947 opened assemblies were added in Cali, Medellín, Cartagena and Contratacion.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Latin America Has Arisen With a Will |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1947 | number = 196 | page =14 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=998}}</ref> Gayle Woolson was again touring several cities of Colombia - Medellín, Cartagena, Barranquilla, Bucaramanga and Mogotes. The members of the Medellín assembly were Francisco Onego R., Bernarda Yepes, Margarita Caicedo, Hernando Jaramillo A., William Gomez M., Dario Echavarria, John Carder, Augusto Mora, Jose Ramos.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Active Young People constitute…|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1947 | number = 188 | page =9 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=1041}}</ref> By July 1947 a regional committee for South America Central American was organizing developments across the continent.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Latin American Administration Develops |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1947 | number = 197 | page =3 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=1003}}</ref> Retrospectively a stated purpose for the committee was to facilitate a shift in the balance of roles from North American guidance and Latin cooperation to Latin guidance and North American cooperation.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = Historical Background of the Panama Temple (part 2)|author=Ruth Pringle|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1972 | number = 493 | page =2 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=50}}</ref> The process was well underway by 1950 and was to be enforced about 1953. Meanwhile, a regional committee oversaw Colombian activities headed by Dr. Saul Hernández out of Bogotá<ref>{{cite magazine | title = International School Marks Latin American Progress|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1947 | number = 198 | page =7 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=1027}}</ref> and Woolson's travels were covered by newspaper and radio press.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = We Can Learn from Latin America|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1947 | number = 199 | page =8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=1040}}</ref>

The second South American Bahá'í Congress was celebrated in [[Santiago, Chile]], in January, 1948. Though Colombia had had more new assemblies form,<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  Latin American News; Plans for Congresses|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1947 | number = 200 | page =8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=1056}}</ref> it was too remote for general logistics. Colombia focused its efforts on welcoming Bahá'ís who attended the [[Pan-American Conference]] instead.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Latin American News; Intensive Teaching Campaign Initialed|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1947 | number = 200 | page =8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=02&page=1056}}</ref> In October 1949 Colombia hosted a conference for Colombian, Ecuadoran and Venezuelan Bahá'ís on the progress of the religion in their areas;<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Latin American News|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1949 | number = 224 | page =10| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=03&page=1036}}</ref> however, all the participants save two teachers came from the Colombian cities of Bogotá, Barranquilla, Cali and Medellín.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Latin American News|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1949 | number = 226 | page =7–8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=03&page=194}}</ref> Then came the prospect of decision making coming from the Latino communities and North Americans supporting their choices. Assemblies across South America failed to reform on their own but several were able to be "activated" during 1950–1.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Notes on latin America|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1951 | number = 243 | page =6| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=03&page=194}}</ref> Pioneers listed for Colombia in 1950 were Gayle Woolson, Elise Schreiber, and Dorothy Campbell.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Inter-America Work Moves Forward|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1950 | number = 234 | page =9| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=03&page=315}}</ref> In 1950, the South American Bahá'ís formed a regional Spiritual Assembly for South America whose first members were Edmund Miessler of [[Brazil]], Margot Worley of Brazil, Eve Nicklin of [[Peru]], Gayle Woolson of [[Colombia]], Esteban Canales of [[Paraguay]], Mercedes Sanchez of Peru, Dr. Alexander Reid of [[Chile]], Rangvald Taetz of [[Uruguay]], and Manuel Vera of Peru.<ref name="statement">{{cite web| title= Comunidad Bahá'í en Chile| publisher= National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of Chile| url= http://data.bahai.cl/bahaichile/webnuevo/com_chile/com_chile.htm| accessdate= 2008-03-03| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080316042132/http://data.bahai.cl/bahaichile/webnuevo/com_chile/com_chile.htm| archivedate= 2008-03-16| deadurl= yes| df= }}</ref> Of the 25 delegates for the 1951 election, 4 were from Colombia.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Latin-American News; Election of Delegates|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1951 | number = 240 |pages=11–12| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=03&page=393}}</ref>
