From 1951 youth groups were being organized for Bahá'ís in Barranquilla and Cali.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = International News; South America; Youth activities in Colombia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1953 | number = 264 | page =7| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=03&page=857}}</ref> In November 1953 pioneers listed for Colombia were Meredith W. Smith and Elton M. Smith,<ref>{{cite magazine| title = National Spiritual Assembly; Third Pioneer Report |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1953 | number = 273 | page =10| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=03&page=976}}</ref> In 1954 Gayle Woolson<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Teaching Missions by Members of Auxiliary Board|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1954 | number = 284 | page =1| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=61}}</ref> and in 1955 Katherine McLaughlin was touring Colombia and nearby countries.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Teaching Missions by Members of Auxiliary Board|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1955 | number = 288 | page =3| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=105}}</ref> Mr. and Mrs. Donald Barrett arrived in Bogota, Colombia, in January, 1955.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Arrivals in Consolidation Areas |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1955 | number = 291 | page =7| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=141}}</ref> In 1956 Woolson went on [[Bahá'í pilgrimage|pilgrimage]] and toured sharing her experience<ref>{{cite magazine| title = American Auxiliary Board Continues Visits throughout Western Hemisphere |author1=Corrine True|author2=Paul E. Haney|author3=Horace Holley|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1956 | number = 303 | page =8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=322}}</ref> and the national center of Colombia was dedicated.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =Hazfratul-Quds of Bogotá, Colombia… |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1957 | number = 312 | page =2| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=473}}</ref>

The next restructuring of the regional assembly came in 1957 when it was split into two - basically northern/eastern South America with the Republics of Brazil, Peru, Colombia, Ecuador, and Venezuela, in Lima, Peru and one of the western/southern South America with the Republics of Argentina, Chile, Uruguay, Paraguay, and Bolivia in Buenos Aires, Argentina.<ref name="stats"/> The convention for northern/eastern Bahá'ís was witnessed by [[Horace Holley (1887–1960)|Horace Holley]] as the representative of Shoghi Effendi.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = International News; Brazil, Peru, Colombia, Ecuador, and Venezuela form National Assembly in Lima |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1957 | number = 317 | page =7| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=558}}</ref> A small book on the Buddha was produced in 1957 by the national assembly.<ref>[http://bahai-library.com/witzel_buda_profeta_dios Buddha - Prophet of God ] by Donald Witzel, Translated by Carmelo Pérez Toledo. Published in The Light Shines in Any Lamp 1 Bogota-Colombia: National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of Peru Originally published as "Buddha: Prophet of God" in Spanish.</ref>  The Colombian Bahá'í community held its first summer school during a national conference in Medelin in January 1958.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Three declarations Result from Loncoche School |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1958 | number = 327 | page =21| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=04&page=768}}</ref> In 1960 the first assemblies were elected at Manizales,<ref>{{cite magazine| title = First Local Spiritual Assembly of…|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1960 | number = 353 | page =19| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=121}}</ref> Pereira,<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Local Assemblies formed, Ridvan 1960 |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1960 | number = 354 | page =12| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=134}}</ref> and Cartagena.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = First Local Spiritual Assembly of… |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1961 | number = 359 | page =13| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=201}}</ref> The Bahá'ís of Cali hosted the 4th convention of the regional assembly.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = National Conventions Recount Growth of Faith; Brazil, Ecuador, Peru, Colombia and Venezuela |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1960 | number = 354 | page =14| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=136}}</ref> In 1960 a three-day conference of the ''World Association of World Federalists'' was held in Germany and was attended by Colombian delegates and Bahá'ís associated with the [[Bahá'í International Community]]. A Colombian delegate responded positively to the suggestion of a relationship between spirituality and the [[World Federalist Movement]].<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Baha'is Contribute Spiritual Teachings to Cologne World Federalist Conference|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1960 | number = 356 |pages=4–5| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=150}}</ref>

There were 19 delegates to the convention to elect the first [[National Spiritual Assembly]] of the Bahá'ís of Colombia in 1961.<ref name="Custodians">{{cite book|author= Rabbani, Ruhiyyih (Ed.) |authorlink=Rúhíyyih Khanum |year= 1992 |title= The Ministry of the Custodians 1957-1963 |publisher= Bahá'í World Centre | pages = 403, 408 |isbn= 0-85398-350-X |url= http://bahai-library.com/uhj_ministry_custodians&chapter=7 }}</ref> The election was witnessed by [[Hand of the Cause]] Shu'á'u'lláh 'Alá'i<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  Hands of Faith Plan Extensive Travels|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1960 | number = 357 | page =4| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=162}}</ref> who made a public address to at the Museum of Colonial Art before the convention.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Six More Latin-American NSAs Report on Formation; Colombia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1961 | number = 365 | page =3| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=289}}</ref> Its first members were:<ref>[http://news.bahai.org/story/ridvan2010/photographs.html Latin American nations elect assemblies for 50th time], Historical Photographs; Elections of 1961</ref> Charles Hornby, A.K. Kalantar, Luis Montenegro, Ervin L. Thomas, Leonor Porras, Jamshid Meghnot, Marjorie Weddell, Habib Rezvani, and Gloria de Fritzsche. Events and the election were covered by [[Revista Semana]] of the May 15, 1961 issue in a full page article.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Bahá'í in the News|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1961 | number = 366 |pages=12–16| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=314}}</ref> In short order the national assembly began publishing its ''Noticias Bahá'is de Colombia'' as its official publication.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = New Latin American NSA's Begin Issuing National News Bulletins|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1961 | number = 367 | page =13| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=331}}</ref> The March–April 1961 issue of ''Cronicos-Israel y America Latina'', published in Colombia, carried an article on the religion.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Bahá'í in the News|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1961 | number = 369 | page =19| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=365}}</ref> It was also in 1961 that the religion was brought to the region of the Guajira department.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = National Conventions Celebrate Victories, Gird Believers for Further Teaching Tasks|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1962 | number = 376 |pages=10–11| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=472}}</ref> In 1962 four new assemblies were elected -one of them all-Indian<ref>{{cite magazine| title = International Council Recounts Victories; Progress Among the Indians of Western Hemisphere|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1962 | number = 378 | page =3| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=505}}</ref> and the national assembly was legally incorporated as well.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  National Incorporation Marks Another Crusade Accomplishment in Colombia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1962 | number = 381 | page =4| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=550}}</ref>

In 1963 the members of the national assemblies of the world were the delegates to elect the first [[Universal House of Justice]]. The Colombian members of the national assembly that year were: Gloria de Fritzsche, Charles Homby, Louis Montenegro, Leonor Porras, Habib Rezvani, Ellen Sims, Ervin Thomas, Wilma Thomas, Stewart M. Waddell; all of whom were able to attend the international connvention together.<ref name="Custodians"/><ref>The list according to the ''Bahá'í News'' differs. This may have been a bi-election or error between the sources. The list according to ''Bahá'í News'' was: Habib Rezvani, Luis Montenegro (chairman), Gloria Fritzschel (recording secretary), Betty Toomes (secretary), Stewart Waddell (treasurer), Charles Hornby, Ellen Sims, Elahi Kalantar (vice-chairman), Leonor Porras.{{cite magazine| title = Annual Convention of Colombia Emphasizes Indian Teaching|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1963 | number = 390 | page =5| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=713}}</ref> In 1963 there were [[Local Spiritual Assemblies]] in: [[Barranquilla]], [[Bogotá]], [[Bucaramanga]], [[Cali]], [[Cartagena, Colombia|Cartagena]], one for the region of [[La Guajira Department|Southeast Guajira]], [[Leticia, Colombia|Leticia]] (Amazonas), [[Manizales]], [[Medellín]], [[Pereira, Colombia|Pereira]], and [[Riohacha]] with smaller groups of Bahá'ís in [[Dibulla, La Guajira|Dibulla]] and [[Ibagué]], and isolated Bahá'ís in [[Maicao]] and [[Palmira, Valle del Cauca|Palmira]] and among it were members of the [[Wayuu]] in the [[La Guajira Department]].<ref name="stats"/>

==Nine Year Plan and the organization of Colombian Bahá'ís==
The Bahá'ís of Colombia were given 10 goals for the ''Nine Year Plan'' designated by the [[Universal House of Justice]] which started in 1964 and Colombia was singled out as having succeeded in its goals so early that several goals were raised in response.<ref name="BN433">{{cite magazine| title = Universal House of Justice Approves Supplementary Goals for Colombia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1967 | number = 433 | page =6| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=566}}</ref> The goals included developing school programs. The 1964 summer school was held in November and covered subjects of newly translated [[The Dawn-Breakers]] and ''The Thief in the Night'', a book by [[Hand of the Cause]] [[William Sears (Bahá'í)|William Sears]] and various[[Bahá'í teachings]] and [[Bahá'í administration|administration]].<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Joyous Spirit Permeates Colombian School|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1964 | number = 397 | page =4| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=794}}</ref> There was also a separate convention/camp for children.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Colombia Holds First Children's Camp|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1964 | number = 397 | page =4| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=05&page=794}}</ref> A new organizational unit, the ''Institute'' or ''Training Institute'', was another goal<ref name="BN433"/><ref>{{Cite journal | first =  | last = Universal House of Justice | authorlink = Universal House of Justice | author2 = Department of the Secretariat | title = Extracts From Messages Written By The Universal House of Justice On The Four Year Plan Related To Training Institutes | booktitle =  | page = 1 | publisher = The Bahá'í Community of Guelph | date = December 1998 | url = http://cluster9.org/heading.php?body=docs_body.htm&head=docs_head.htm | accessdate = 2010-05-12 | journal =  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110725181347/http://cluster9.org/heading.php?body=docs_body.htm&head=docs_head.htm | archive-date = 2011-07-25 | dead-url = yes | df =  }}</ref> and Colombia's first one began to organize and operate in 1965 as part of initiatives focused on the Indian population in the La Guajira region.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Colombians Set for Intensive Indian Teaching|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1965 | number = 412 | page =6| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=178}}</ref> There were also several series of progressive institute courses used among the Bahá'ís.<ref name="BN433"/> A regional conference on the progress of the religion in the region was called by the [[Hands of the Cause]] in the western hemisphere in the summer of 1965 at the Bogotá national center along with representatives of the national assembly of Ecuador, Colombia and of the communities of Bogota, Barranquilla, Bucaramanga, Cali, Manizalez, Pereira, [[Ibagué]], and [[Ciénaga de Oro]].<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Bogota, Colombia Hosts Regional Teaching Congress|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1966 | number = 419 | page =5| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=297}}</ref> By winter 1965 there were many Baha'is among both the Colombian and Venezuelan [[Wayuu|Guajiros]], about 1,000 on the Colombian side and 1,500 on the Venezuelan side.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Colombia-Venezuela join Forces in Indian Teaching|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1966 | number = 420 |pages=5–6| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=313}}</ref> Another stated goal was in the realm of international cooperation<ref name="BN433"/> - the newly developing Indian Institute of Riohacha was shared with the Venezuelans during the first Guajiro Teacher Training Institute held at Riohacha. Among the participants in this first training were: Rosalba Pimienta, Tiana Arpushana, Tomas Pimienta, Juan Artiz Pimienta, Martha Duarte Arpushana, Maria Teresa Duarte Arpushana, Carmen Pimienta Arpushana, and Martha Epiaya all of Colombia and Rogelio Hernández, José Martin Sempron, Cecilia del Carmen Iguaran, and Maria Cecilía González all of Venezuela. The next institute was held in January 1966 at which the dedication of the building was set and the building, called the ''Villa Rahmat'', as an Institute was completed by August.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Five Indian Delegates Attend Colombian Convention|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1966 | number = 425 | page =8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=400}}</ref> After constructing the Guajiro Teaching Institute the community united in sending financial aid to Kenya, thus fulfilling that goal.<ref name="BN433"/> Further to supporting international cooperation among Bahá'í communities the three national assemblies of Brazil, Colombia and Peru joined forces in 1965-66 and sent material resources and traveling teachers for the development of the religion in the elevated Amazon area<ref>{{cite magazine| title = South America Meets New Challenges|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1966 | number = 426 | page =6| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=418}}</ref> and Colombia in particular sent pioneers beyond its national borders.<ref name="BN433"/> First contact with the [[Archipelago of San Andrés, Providencia and Santa Catalina]] for the Bahá'ís came in 1966 when [[Helen Hornby]]<ref>Helen Hornby is well known as the compiler of reference volumes before computerized text search tools existed - {{cite book | last = Bahá'u'lláh | first = | authorlink = Bahá'u'lláh |last2 = 'Abdu'l-Bahá| first2 = | author2-link ='Abdu'l-Bahá |last3 = Effendi| first3 = Shoghi| author3-link =Shoghi Effendi |author4=Helen Hornby | title = Lights of Guidance - A Bahá'í Reference File  |edition = 3rd| publisher = Bahá'í Publishing Trust, 1999| year = 1988 | location = New Delhi | url =http://bahai-library.com/hornby_lights_guidance&chapter=1#1 | origyear = 1983 | isbn = 978-81-85091-46-4 }}</ref> and her husband pioneered there.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Colombia Opens San Andre and Providence Islands|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1966 | number = 426 | page =7| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=419}}</ref> By 1967 there was an election of a local assembly in San Andrés, with a community of nearly one hundred members and sixty-four on Providencia and across Colombia the goal of Bahá'ís living in 100 localities was more than doubled and one locality has been established in each of (then) sixteen departments and other civic divisions.<ref name="BN433"/> By 1967 eight local assemblies were formed among the [[Motilone Barí|Motilones]].<ref name="BN433"/><ref>{{cite magazine| title = Motilón Indians of Colombia Arise to Accept Faith|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1967 | number = 436 |pages=5–7| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=06&page=617}}</ref>
In late 1967 into 1968 Vicente Montezuma, a Panamanian [[Guaymí]] who had previously served in the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of Panama, pioneered to the rural areas of Colombia and promulgated the religion especially among the [[Choco languages|Choco speaking]] Indians.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Guaymi Teacher Wins Choco Indians of Colombia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1968 | number = 446 |pages=8–9| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=124}}</ref> Almost overlapping his trip [[Hand of the Cause]] [[Ruhiyyih Khanum]] traveled through Venezuela and Colombia from February 1968.<ref name="BN449">{{cite magazine| title = 'Amatu'l Baha Ruhfyyih Khanum Visits Venezuela and Colombia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1968 | number = 449 |pages=4–7, 10| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=146}}</ref> On the evening of February 29 she arrived at the Villa Rahmat, the Guajiro Indian Institute. The next evening she showed slides of her trips to Panama, Bolivia, and Argentina Indian to about thirty Riohacha adult and children Bahá'ís. Soon she traveled with local Bahá'ís to the sea salt harvest sands at [[Manaure, La Guajira|Manaure]]. From there the group went to the homeland of the [[Yukpa]](Yuko) in the [[Cesar Department]] where she camped in a [[Plantain (cooking)|Plaintain]] grove. There she promulgated the religion indirectly, by being known as a Bahá'í who was interested in their craft work even among avowed Bahá'ís. From there she and her group ascended into a more remote region and a machete wounded foot of a Bahá'í was tended. Later she offered that though she was raised largely in "city life" she had served an example of travel in the remote regions.<ref name="BN449"/> From there she visited the Bahá'ís in Barranquilla and Bogotá where she also gave talks. Upon reaching Bogotá several newspapers covered her work -  El Espectador, carried a featured story "El Bahá'í Busca la Unidad Humana" by Margarita Vidal Garcia. While in the area she met [[Leonora Armstrong]].<ref name="BN449"/> Meanwhile, in May one of the first Bahá'ís in San Andrés insisted on a Bahá'í funeral which in turn was covered by local radio and attended by some 500 people including civic and religious leaders and resulted in a large venue for the observance of the Bahá'í Holy Day, the [[Bahá'í calendar#Holy days|Declaration of the Báb]].<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Passing of Baha'is Proclaims Faith|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1968 | number = 450 | page =18| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=198}}</ref>

Cross border activity in La Guajira continued in 1969 with Venezuelan Guajiro Bahá'ís traveling in Colombia and Colombian Guajiro Bahá'ís attending activities in Venezuela.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Guajiro Indians Demonstrate Strong Baha'i Potential|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1969 | number = 450 | page =5| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=321}}</ref> At the 1969 national convention a number of Yukon/Yukpa delegates attended.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =Delegates from the Motilón tribe…|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1970 | number = 468 | page =13| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=521}}</ref> The October summer school was held in Cali.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =Believers irom Bogotá, Cali, Jamundi, Maizales,…|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1970 | number = 468 | page =17| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=525}}</ref> And a training institute was established in the Chocó region.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =Youth, "in a wunderful atmosphere of love and happiness,"… |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1970 | number = 469 | page =19| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=547}}</ref>

In May 1970 an all-Guajiro Bahá'í conference brought together some 200 Bahá'ís from the region for talks and lessons offered in Spanish and Guajira languages including a history of the religion in the region including noting 110 local assemblies being elected that year: 57 in Colombia: 53 in Venezuela, as well as the dedication of a local Bahá'í House of Worship.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = An International Conference: Venezuela - Colombia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1970 | number = 473 | page =19| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=619}}</ref> In April [[Hand of the Cause]] [[Enoch Olinga]] took a trip through Colombia<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Group of Bahá'ís attending National Conference…|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1970 | number = 476 | page =8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=668}}</ref> and in July a continental conference of Bahá'ís was held in Bolivia at which several delegates from Colombia attended<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Continental and Oceanic Conferences Promote Goals of Nine Year Plan; Official welcome extended|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1970 | number = 476 | page =3| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=663}}</ref> while others from Colombia worked in Brazil.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Victories won in Brazil|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1970 | number = 477 | page =14| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=694}}</ref> In September new pioneer Bahá'ís reached [[Santa Lucía, Atlántico]] - by 1971 there were over 400 Bahá'ís including the mayor, three classes begun, a regional convention on the progress of the religion, and an institute were operating.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Sta. Lucia- A Success Story|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1972 | number = 483 | page =21| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=69}}</ref> In 1970 about fifteen people accounted as the active core of the community in Cali.<ref name="1970s">{{Harv|The Ruhi Institute|July 1991|p=1}}</ref> They began what would turn into - in about two decades - the [[Ruhi Institute]] (see below.)

An informal summary of the community in 1971 showed about 1000 Bahá'ís and expectations of doubling the number of assemblies among the Guajiro Bahá'ís.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  Mass Teaching is the only way to tell the people in time|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1971 | number = 483 | page =23| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=07&page=831}}</ref> In 1972 Guajiro Bahá'ís attended the dedication of the Panamanian [[Bahá'í House of Worship#Panama City.2C Panama|Bahá'í House of Worship]]<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Panamanian Temple: Dedication and International Conference; Dedication of the Temple|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1972 | number = 496 | page =9| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=128}}</ref> and the Bahá'í population of Santa Lucía was reported at 1200 and had reached neighboring villages during a follow-up conference in at Manaure.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  Him Will the Faithful Spirit Strengthen; Pioneer Teaching Trip Report-Baskin/Hansen|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1972 | number = 496 |pages=14–16| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=253}}</ref> In 1973 Luis Montenegro, former long term member of the National Assembly of Colombia died while climbing the mountains of the Yukpa(Yuko), or Motilon, Indians.<ref name="BN521">{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Colombia; Friends in Cali meet Counsellor Armstrong|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1974 | number = 521 | page =2| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=723}}</ref> At the close of the Nine Year Plan changes had indeed been wrought in Colombia.

==Projects and developments, wider growth==
In 1974 a conference was held in Cali with Bahá'ís from Venezuela, Ecuador, Colombia attending and now appointed [[Institution of the Counsellors|Continental Counselor]] Leonora Armstrong attended.<ref name="BN521"/> A national training institute was dedicated.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Colombia; Goals of Plan considered|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1974 | number = 523 | page =8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=777}}</ref> The first of the [[Paez people]] joined the religion in 1974 due to the service of a Panamanian Bahá'í traveling in Colombia.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Panama; First Paez Indians enrolled in Cause|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1974 | number = 521 | page =4| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=725}}</ref> In 1975 [[Ruhiyyih Khanum]] returned to Colombia but this time it was on the side of the tropical forest during the [[Green Light Expedition]] recording her travel up the Amazon river and through other rivers and adjoining lands.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  The green light expedition; A journey of friendship by Rúhíyyih Khánum to the Indian tribes of South America|author=David Walker|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1975 | number = 521 |pages=2–13| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=08&page=938}}</ref> She entered [[Leticia, Amazonas|Leticia]],<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  The green light expedition: part III; Youth told of their responsibilities for future|author=Anthony Roy Worley|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1975 | number = 521 |pages=16–17| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=109}}</ref> where she was interviewed by reporters and met with a [[Ticuna language|Ticuna]] speaking chief and then citizens of the village.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  The green light expedition: part IV; Youth told of their responsibilities for future|author=Anthony Roy Worley|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1976 | number = 521 |pages=1–8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=186}}</ref> By 1978 a Bahá'í center was raised in Leticia.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  Around the World; Colombia |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1978 | number = 567 | page =15| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=759}}</ref> In 1976 the first citizen of [[List of islands of South America#Caribbean Sea islands|Archipiélago de San Bernardo]] joined the religion in 1976.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  Around the World; Colombia; Pioneer reports gain in islands|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1976 | number = 543 |pages=7–8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=297}}</ref> Print materials were being produced in Colombia and circulated there and in Ecuador.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  Around the World; Ecuador; Children's conference nets 17 declarations|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1976 | number = 545 | page =8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=327}}</ref> The religion was introduced to [[Sogamoso]].<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  Around the World; Colombia; Children's classes part of teaching project|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1977 | number = 551 | page =14| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=454}}</ref> The fifth All-Guajira Conference was held in July in Venezuela.<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  Around the World; Venezuela; Fifth All-Guajira Conference held at Los Mochos, Zulia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1977 | number = 559 | page =8| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=599}}</ref> In 1977 the Brazil, Colombia and Peru Bahá'í communities formed a committee to coordinate efforts in the border regions deep in the Amazon.<ref name=BN560>{{cite magazine| title =  Around the World; New Amazon Committee notes teaching success|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1977 | number = 560 | page =16| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=09&page=626}}</ref> A 1978 institute covered the relationship between the elected and appointed aspects of [[Bahá'í administration]] for some 30 Bahá'ís in [[Riohacha]].<ref name=BN560/> In 1980 the [[Bahá'í International Community]] reported on projects Bahá'ís communities had carried out for the [[International Year of the Child]] - the national assembly of Colombia published a compilation ''Educacion Espiritual de los Niños''<ref>{{cite magazine| title = IYC report: A worldwide round-up of Bahá'í activities supporting the International Year of the Child; Ongoing Programs-4. Publications for and Concerning Children | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1980 | number = 592 | page =4| url=http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=214}}</ref> and the Amatu'l-Baha Ruhiyyih Khanum International Institute of the Amazon Region was dedicated February in Leticia.<ref name="BN594">{{cite magazine| title =  Border teaching - Colombia, Ecuador seek closer ties to proclaim Cause | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1980 | number = 594 |pages=8–9| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=334}}</ref> In April on the west side of Colombia and the Bahá'ís of [[Pasto]] hosted the first Colombian-Ecuadorian Bahá'í ''Frontier Conference'' on the promulgation of the religion in the area with about 120 participants. Under the cooperation of the two national assemblies a commission was appointed to coordinate efforts in the area. Among the initiatives reviewed was the Ecuadorian ''Bahá'í Radio'' station who's broadcast covers some of Ecuador and Colombia.<ref name="BN594"/> In addition to more Bahá'ís the goal's included the responsibility for children's classes, women's activities, and assembly development programs and was centered from the Puerta Tejada Ruhi Institute and graduation was the act of explaining each completed course satisfactorily to at least five other Bahá'ís. Attendees at the conference also reviewed the events surrounding the death of [[Enoch Olinga]], his wife, and three of their children, as well as the life of service of [[Rahmatu'lláh Muhájir]] who had died in Ecuador the year before.

In 1982 some 1,300 Baha'is from 42 countries gathered August in Quito, the second of five such gatherings.  13 Continental Counsellors, representatives of 24 of the 29 National Spiritual Assemblies in Latin America and the Caribbean, and members of 21 Indian tribes from Bolivia, Brazil, Canada, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Panama, Peru, United States and Venezuela attended. The Conferences were dedicated to the memory of [[Bahiyyih Khánum]].<ref>{{cite magazine| title =  International Conferences Quito: Riding the 'high tide' of victory | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1982 | number = 619 | page =3| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=736}}</ref>

The idea for a ''Trail of Light'' occurred during preparations for the first Bahá'í Native Council (see [[Bahá'í Faith and Native Americans]]) in 1978. Another inspiration for the Trail of Light was the concept of promulgating the religion among the indigenous peoples in the [[Pacific Rim]] that was described by the [[Hand of the Cause]] [[Rahmátu'llah Muhájir]] in 1978. The Trail of Light, also known as ''Camino del Sol'', was defined as a process whereby native Bahá'ís engaged with diverse native peoples about a number of issues including promulgating their religion as well as organizing councils for the people and encouraged discovery of mutual cultural links across the native peoples. The first ''Trail of Light'' traveling trip by 22 members of the religion occurred spontaneously immediately after the council.<ref name="BN594 Council">{{cite magazine | title = 'Trail of Light' Native American teaching effort follows North American Baha'i Native Council |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1980 | number = 594|ISSN=0195-9212 |pages=6–7 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=254}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | title = Alaska - A Baha'i community grows, matures |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1981 | number = 607 |ISSN=0195-9212 |pages=1–6 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=503}}</ref> In 1985 the Trail of Light project began its work in Colombia.<ref>{{cite magazine | title = 'Train of Light' completes successful visit|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1985 | number = 656 |ISSN=0195-9212 |pages=1–3 | url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=493}}</ref> Among the participants were two youth from the Guaymi tribe in Panama; six members from the Guajiros, the Colombo-Venezuelan tribe, and two youth from the Paez, a tribe in southern Colombia. They first traveled to the Guajira region and re-affirmed the religion among the Bahá'ís there and the group performed dances which inspired the Guajiros to offer their own dance, the Chichamaya, which had been illegal. The group was invited to the local high school where the Guaymis shared the story of the impact of the religion among their people (see [[Bahá'í Faith in Panama]].) The group was then invited to the elementary school. From Guajira the group headed to [[Valledupar]] and then on to the homeland of the [[Arhuaco]] tribe in the [[Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta]]. There the group met with the leadership, the Mamos, or elders of the community for permission to present the message they had come to give. Various of the group presented to the Mamos including the Guaymi and their interpretation of their own prophecies. An elder shared that the Arhuaco had a similar prophecy. The Trail of Light group was allowed to make their presentations and exchanges of dances and talks followed. From there the group traveled to see the [[Yukpa]](Yuko) tribe. With the Yuko the group was able to hold a unity feast and shared dances and stayed for three days before heading home.

Since its inception the religion has had involvement in [[socio-economic development]] beginning by giving greater freedom to women,<ref name="iranhistory">{{cite web| last = Momen  | first = Moojan  | title = History of the Baha'i Faith in Iran  | work = draft "A Short Encyclopedia of the Baha'i Faith"  | publisher = Bahai-library.com  | url = http://bahai-library.com/momen_encyclopedia_iran#9.%20Social%20and%20economic%20development | accessdate = 2009-10-16}}</ref> promulgating the promotion of female education as a priority concern,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Kingdon  | first = Geeta Gandhi | title  = Education of women and socio-economic development | journal = Baha'i Studies Review | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | year = 1997 | url =http://bahai-library.com/kingdon_education_women_development }}</ref> and that involvement was given practical expression by creating schools, agricultural coops, and clinics.<ref name="iranhistory"/> Since the 1970s the Colombian Bahá'ís have developed a pair of important institutions - FUNDAEC, and the Ruhi Institute.

===FUNDAEC===
{{main|FUNDAEC}}
Against a backdrop of serious social disruption and violence across Colombia Bahá'ís turned to service to the people living in the countryside. In 1974 [[FUNDAEC]]<ref>FUNDAEC is different from [[FUNDESCU]] though there are many similarities. FUNDAEC is the Colombian NGO based on Bahá'í consultations with Colombians starting in the 1970s and developed a number of projects like a secondary curriculum centered on skill development for living in the countryside and minimized [[urbanization]] for example. FUNDESCU is an older (from the 1950s) NGO in Panama based on Bahá'í consultations with Panamanian Indians and developed a system of schools serving largely remote areas. An agricultural project was attempted in the 1990s and was in fact based on cooperation between the Panamanian and Colombian NGOs but it failed from differences.{{Citation|last=Rhodenbaugh |first=Molly Marie |title=The Ngöbe Baha'is of Panama |work=MA Thesis in Anthropology |publisher=[[Texas Tech University]] |date=August 1999 |url=http://etd.lib.ttu.edu/theses/available/etd-10272008-31295016514407/unrestricted/31295016514407.pdf |pages=119–123 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110815213017/http://etd.lib.ttu.edu/theses/available/etd-10272008-31295016514407/unrestricted/31295016514407.pdf |archivedate=2011-08-15 |df= }}</ref> was founded by group of professors at the [[University of Valle]].<ref name="Club">{{Cite news | title = Baha'i-inspired educational system for the poor of the world honored by the Club of Budapest  | newspaper = Bahá'í World News Service  | location = Frankfurt, Germany   | publisher =  Bahá’í International Community  | date = 22 December 2002  | url =  http://news.bahai.org/story/185  | accessdate = 2010-05-08}}</ref> According to Gustav Correa, director of FUNDAEC, it was originally inspired by a quotation from [[Bahá'u'lláh]]  -  "Baha'u'llah talks about man as 'a mine rich in gems of inestimable value.'  He says that 'education can, alone, cause it to reveal its treasures, and enable mankind to benefit therefrom'.<ref name="Club"/> In 1983 Gustavo Correa presented on the FUNDAEC project to [[Association for Bahá'í Studies]] 8th annual Conference.<ref name="BN634"/> In 1985 an advisor of a development committee assisting the [[Anís Zunúzí Bahá'í School]] visited the FUNDAEC project in Cali to look for insights in development work.<ref name="BN634"/>

One of the authors was [[Farzam Arbab]] and president of FUNDAEC from 1974 to 1988,<ref>{{cite web
 |url          = http://silk-pen.com/product/methodologies-and-development-strategies-farzam-aarbab
 |title        = Methodologies and Development Strategies - Farzam Aarbab
 |date         = 
 |website      = 
