 |access-date  = Oct 9, 2017
 |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090425163145/http://silk-pen.com/product/methodologies-and-development-strategies-farzam-aarbab
 |archive-date = 2009-04-25
 |dead-url     = yes
 |df           = 
}}</ref> would also serve in several capacities for the religion including being a member of the National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of Colombia, a Continental Counsellor, appointed to the International Teaching Centre and eventually elected to the [[Universal House of Justice]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite news | title = Two new members elected to Universal House of Justice | date = 2010-03-20 | accessdate = 2010-03-20 | publisher = Bahá'í World News Service | url = http://news.bahai.org/story/762 | author= Bahá'í International Community}}</ref>

FUNDAEC has instituted a number of development projects: the ''Centro Universitario de Bienestar Rural'',<ref name="Principles">{{Cite web | last =  Arbab | first = Farzam | first2 = Gustavo | last2 =  Correa| first3 = Francia | last3 = de Valcarcel  | title = FUNDAEC: Its Principles and its Activities | work =  | publisher = CELATER, Cali, Colombia | year = 1988 | url = http://www.fundaec.org/en/institution/celater_doc.htm | accessdate = 2010-05-08| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100404205610/http://www.fundaec.org/en/institution/celater_doc.htm| archivedate= 4 April 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> the "Tutorial Learning System" or "SAT" (the Spanish acronym for "Sistema de Aprendizaje Tutorial") and a [[micro-finance]] Project. The SAT was particularly successful with cutting the process of [[urbanization]], increases in democratic behavior and aspects of gender equality, extra curricular activities in communities, stopping migratory movement of populations, and established public-private cooperation in Colombia.<ref name="Rural"/> By 2002 the SAT system was in use in Honduras, Guatemala, Ecuador, Venezuela, Panama, Costa Rica, Brazil, Colombia and the first phases of the implementation of the program have started in Zambia.<ref name="Club"/><ref>{{Cite web|title=FUNDAEC, Colombia: Gustavo Correa Development Schools are Teaching Self Reliance |work=Change the World -- Best Practice Award |publisher=Club of Budapest |url=http://www.clubofbudapest.org/p-aw-fundaec-correa.php |accessdate=2010-05-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100812151515/http://www.clubofbudapest.org/p-aw-fundaec-correa.php |archivedate=2010-08-12 |df= }}</ref><ref>[http://www.bic.org/statements-and-reports/bic-statements/96-0430.htm Two Bahá'í International Community Projects: Cameroon and Zambia]{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Parallel to SAT, FUNDAEC began a [[micro-finance]] initiative as well.<ref>{{Cite journal | title = In Colombia, a microcredit project aims to re-awaken community solidarity | journal = One Country | volume = 1996 | issue = April–June | publisher = Bahá'í International Community | location = La Arrobleda, Cauca, Colombia | year = 1996 | url = http://info.bahai.org/article-1-8-1-10.html| issn = | accessdate = 2010-05-08}}</ref>

===Ruhi Institute===
{{main|Ruhi Institute}}
In Colombia the [[Ruhi Institute]], a [[Bahá'í study circle]], began as an initiative of the community with a commitment starting in 1970.<ref name="1970s"/>  In 1980 a Ruhi Institute was operating in the border area where Ecuador and Colombia meet.<ref name="BN594"/> About 1980 one of the Auxiliary Board members in Colombia entered into a process of consultation with several rural communities around the town of Puerto Tejada in order to help them identify steps. they could take to improve their own social conditions.<ref name="1980s">{{Harv|The Ruhi Institute|July 1991|pp=46–7}}</ref> An early aim was to establish nurseries and kindergartens. In 1983 it published its first course ''Principles and Beliefs, Course 1: Life and Death''.<ref name="MacEoin">{{cite web | last = MacEoin | first = Denis |author2=Collins, William  | title =  Life after death | work = The Babi and Baha'i Religions: An Annotated Bibliography | publisher = Greenwood Press's ongoing series of Bibliographies and Indexes in Religious Studies| url = http://bahai-library.com/books/biblio/life.after.death.html | accessdate = 2010-05-09 | page = 1 (# 14)}}</ref> The courses developed as a "Core Activities Initiative".<ref>[http://www.tc.edu/centers/epe/htm%20articles/GervaisBahaiFaith_22feb08.doc Baha’i Faith and Peace Education] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427024821/http://www.tc.edu/centers/epe/htm%20articles/GervaisBahaiFaith_22feb08.doc# |date=2012-04-27 }} by Marie Gervais, University of Alberta Canada</ref> In 1983 there was discussion of using the Ruhi Institute process in the Dominican Republic<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The World; Dominican Republic | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1983 | number = 626 | page =11| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=876}}</ref> and in Puerto Rico.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The World; Puerto Rico | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1983 | number = 629 | page =16| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=10&page=938}}</ref> In 1984 Bahá'í Counsellors and Auxiliary Board members from Colombia, the Dominican Republic, Panama, Puerto Rico and Venezuela met at the Ruhi Institute in Puerto Tejada and discussed the Ruhi Institute courses<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The World; Colombia | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1984 | number = 636 | page =13| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=115}}</ref> and the Ruhi courses were used in the Central African Republic.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Central African Republic - Mobile institute aids teaching, deepening | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1984 | number = 641 |pages=6–7| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=208}}</ref> Counsellors and representatives of 17 National Spiritual Assemblies in the Caribbean basin and Latin America gathered in St. Lucia to introduce and study materials prepared at the Ruhi Institute in Colombia<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The World; St. Lucia | ISSN=0195-9212|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=November 1984 | number = 644 | page =13| url =http://bahai-news.info/viewer.erb?vol=11&page=274}}</ref> and Honduran Bahá'ís attended the Cali Ruhi Institute with the intention of returning to Honduras as trainers in the Ruhi methods.<ref name="BN648"/> In 1987 the institute wrote its first course book on the education of children.<ref name="1980s"/> In 1988 the national assembly decided to seek legal recognition for the Ruhi Institute by incorporating it as an organization with its own Board of Directors appointed by the assembly.<ref name="organized">{{Harv|The Ruhi Institute|July 1991|p=55}}</ref> It dedicates its efforts to the development of human resources for the spiritual, social, and cultural development of the [[Colombian people]]. Although its center is in the town of Puerto Tejada in the [[Cauca Department|department of Cauca]], its area of influence extends throughout the entire country. Especially in recent years, its educational programs have been adopted by an increasing number of agencies worldwide.<ref name="organized"/>

If individuals developed interests in contributing to society beyond those of the formal Ruhi courses they were introduced to the opportunities provided by FUNDAEC.<ref>{{Harv|The Ruhi Institute|July 1991|pp=49–50}}</ref>

==Recent situation==

===Demographics===
In 2000 the [[World Christian Encyclopedia]] estimated some 64,000 Bahá'ís in Colombia ranking it as among the top 20 Bahá'í communities of the world.<ref>[http://www.adherents.com/largecom/com_bahai.html The Largest Baha'i Communities; Top 20 Largest National Baha'i Populations] Adherents.com</ref> The [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] (relying mostly on the World Christian Encyclopedia) estimated there were 70,512 Bahá'ís (0.2% of the population) in the country in 2005,<ref name="WCE-05"/>  and about the same in 2010.<ref name=ARDA2010/> [[Wolfram Alpha]] estimated 0.1531% of Colombians or almost 69,000 people were Bahá'ís in 2010.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia | title = Colombia: population, capital, cities, GDP, map, flag, currency, languages, ... | encyclopedia = Wolfram Alpha | volume = Online | publisher = Wolfram - Alpha (curated data) | date = March 13, 2010 | url = http://www.wolframalpha.com/entities/countries/colombia/5g/th/so | accessdate = 2010-06-06}}</ref> 

===First local House of Worship===
In 2012 the Universal House of Justice announced the first local [[Bahá'í Houses of Worship]] would be built. One of these was specified in [[Norte del Cauca, Colombia]].<ref>{{cite news | title =Plans to build new Houses of Worship announced | newspaper =Bahá'í World News Service | publisher =Bahá’í International Community | date =22 April 2012 | url = http://news.bahai.org/story/906| accessdate = 2012-04-22}}</ref> The design for this local House of Worship, to be situated in Agua Azul, was unveiled on 14 September 2014.<ref>{{cite news | title =Design of Colombian House of Worship unveiled | newspaper =Bahá'í World News Service | publisher =Bahá’í International Community | date =16 September 2014 | url = http://news.bahai.org/story/1020| accessdate = 2016-09-16}}</ref>

